\'93Up,\'94 I said, causing Harold Sr. to shift his weight off his knee.\
He lifted his chin at his son and looked at Irene\'92s wrists.  Harold Jr. kneeled across Irene\'92s ankles and shifted his grip to her wrists.  Senior grabbed her by the shoulders, lifting her off the ground.  I threw the fabric along the floor underneath her, grabbing it on the other side.  I pulled it as tight across her arms as I could, making a second pass of fabric from her neck to her chest.  Harold lifted again and I tossed the remainder of the fabric under her head.\
A single emphatic word came out through her apron gag, clearly a \'93stop!\'94.\
Pausing with a handful of fabric and some random cabling between us, I looked her in the eyes.\
\'93Oh, were we not done talking?\'94\
She said something that was lost to the gag.  The steel was gone from her eyes.\
\'93This is your last shot,\'94 I told her as my hand hovered over the gag.  \'93Got it?\'94\
She nodded and I slid the gag down under her chin.\
\'93You have the trigger,\'94 she said.  \'93It can disarm the bomb.\'94\
Keeping one hand on the fabric, I used the other to pull the tube out of my bra.  I considered unscrewing the cap one-handed, but decided against it.  I dropped the fabric to her chest and cautiously removed the top.  Both Harolds shifted, uneasy.\
\'93Tell me what to do,\'94 I said.\
\'93You see the button, and around it is a switch.  It has writing on it.\'94\
I leaned back against the wall to steady myself.\
\'93Yeah, I see it.  There\'92s a \'91B\'92 and a \'91P\'92.\'94\
\'93You can turn the switch.  Turn it towards the \'91B\'92.\'94\
